The rule of English, therefore, is that both the tense of the main sentence and the tense of the subordinate clause are understood relative to the speaker of the main sentence (not John, but the person who speaks 
    through 
    ).

The non-logical connectives of selma'o JOI, BIhI, and GAhO are also permitted between tenses. One application is to specify intervals not by size, but by their end-points ( 
    bi'obelongs to selma'o BIhI, and connects the end-points of an ordered interval, like English 
    from ... to):

